review_blob: Bottled 2003. Thin pour, minimal to no head. Nice clear amber color. Almost no carbonation (but of course its a barleywine).  Very sweet malty floral scent.  Thick syrupy mouthfeel, floral sweet malty taste and high alcohol level all hit the palate at the same time.  The assertive mouthfeel stays syrupy on the way down.  I love the taste, but the mouthfeel makes everything feel cloying.

Bottle. Pours a nice cloudy yellow.  Decent head.  Smells nice, too- very citrusy and spicey.  Taste is very lemony mixed with spice (cloves?), too. However, there was too much of that lemon-citrus taste, a bit over-powering.  Not bad for the price, but not on my list of must-haves.

Bottle. Dark brown, opaque pour.  Suitably frothy head.  Spicey and fruity smell.  Taste is caramel sweet, with some spice.  The sweetness, alcohol and very low carbonation make for a heavy but pleasing mouthfeel.  Very nice brown.

Dark, oak, cloudy pour with a substantial head.  Aroma of spices with a spicy citrusy taste.  Malty, but well balanced by the alcohol and carbonation.  A bit tart, but still works well.  A fine dubbel.

Bottle. Dark yellowish-brown pour, good head that fizzed out quickly but never disappeared.  Nice spiced wheaty taste.  Mouthfeel is heavier than average for a wheatbeer.  I loved the taste, but there was inadequate carbonation and hops.  By the end of the glass the tastiness was stlil there, but lacking the tart kick that a little more hops and carbonation could provide. Felt flat at the end.  Still, the clove/spice taste makes it worth a try.

Bottle. Poured a good ruddy-brown, but with a thin head.  Cherry and raisin sweet malt flavor with some alcohol.  Moderate mouthfeel- the brew _looks_ like it should be heavier than it is.  If you find the palate a little thin, I think the flavor should still carry you through.

Pours a deep reddish black, though it is practically opaque in the glass.  Decent light brown head that thinned out a bit faster than Id like to see on a stout.  Aroma is one of heavy malt, some chocolate.  Uncomplicated (ie well-mixed) taste of malt and oat-nuttiness, some vanilla and even some chocolate; rounded out with a twinge of hops.  Mouthfeel is very heavy and also uncomplicated from lips to throat, a perfect creamy, uncloying sip, with a hint of the alcohol near the end.  Very satisfying.

Bottled Dec 2001.  Nice dark amber brown pour.  Minimal tan head.  Aroma filled with caramel, some spice, with a flowery presence. Taste is a sweet caramel, malt, with oaken and (maybe?) a little earthiness too.  The alcohol asserts itself in the back of the throat which well serves as a counter to the creamy sweetness that some may find a little cloying (but of course this _is_ a barley wine).  Nice mellow aftertaste that does not hang around too long.

An almost opaque yellow beer, the head was minimal then quickly vanished.  The aroma and taste is extremely flowery and sweet with a hint of hops to keep it the sweetness in check. The creamy smooth mouthfeel is nice, but I would have liked to see a little more carbonation.  Dont taste the (supposedly) 10% alcohol at all.

Poured with a scary amount of clumpy sediment- it looked like a beer version pearl tea.  A little bit of sediment is fine, but globs of it plunking out of the bottle did not appear appetizing. OK tannish-brown head.  A musty odor and a musty, earthy, malty sweet taste.  Perhaps I had a bad bottle.
Decent head. Dark brown veer. Sweet brackish aroma. _Extremely_ sweet.  First sip tasted like cola.  Tastes like molasses.  Syrupy sweet aftertaste.  Way too sweet.

Beautiful dark brown pour, thick tan head leaves lace around the glass at every sip. Caramel and faintly nutty aroma.  Dark yeast sediment floated to the bottom of the glass.  Taste was a combination of light malty, spicy  sweetness on the tongue.  Ample carbonation plus the hit of alcohol gives each sip a little tart kick in the back of the throat. Good flavor without feeling heavy.  Great combination of sweet start and tart finish.  One of my favorite browns.

Bottle. Poured a murky yellow with a small head.  Faint aroma sweet and flowery.  A nicely carbonated crisp, clean brew.  Some spiced, mustard taste, but not very noticeable; helps drive home the crisp mouthfeel.  Very drinkable, especially on a warmer day.

Bottled. Poured with a nice thick head. Aroma was a sweet malty scent.  Beautiful dark brown color.   The type of nice malty flavor I enjoy.  Mouthfeel was nice on the tongue, but heavy down the throat; there was a thick sweet,malty aftertaste that stuck to the back of the throat long after taking a sip.  Not bad at all, probably better if paired with a meal.

Beautiful dark color, nice malty aroma. Head dissipates quickly. Slightly fizzy, but tastes much lighter than it appears. A little fruit sweetness, but not as thick a taste and mouthfeel as the color/aroma would suggest.
Tart cherry (almost a lambic), sharp hit of alcohol with citrusy sweetness.  Very fizzy beer. The head dissolves quickly but never disappears.  Not to my taste, but I know many who would like it.

Thick black pour. Decent head.  Very chocolatey smell.  Taste of thick chocolate, some raisin, and maybe a hint of vanilla sweetness.  Palate started well, but finishes with a malty-caramel syrup taste that felt a little too heavy.

Sour balsamic vinegar aroma. No head, no fizz, and sour mouthfeel.  Dark mahogany color.  Grape syrup taste, tart, but just sweet enough to counter.  Once youre past the smell, its actually easy to swallow...
